msgid ".. image:: /images/text/working_text_decorative_3.png"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:54
msgid "An underline was added the :guilabel:`Character` tab."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:56
msgid "For example, lets underline this bit of text. Select the text. Then go to the :guilabel:`Character` tab and to :guilabel:`Add Property` at the bottom, and type \"underline\". You will see :guilabel:`Text Decoration` in the list. Select this. Now, toggle :guilabel:`Underline`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:60
msgid ".. image:: /images/text/working_text_decorative_4.png"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:60
msgid "Here, we went back to the :guilabel:`Paragraph` tab, and only changed the font family."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:62
msgid "Now when you go back to the :guilabel:`Paragraph` tab, and adjust the font, the underline is kept on our original selection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:66
msgid ".. image:: /images/text/working_text_decorative_5.png"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:66
msgid "Same as above. Each of these samples uses a different font. Because in the :guilabel:`Character` tab we only adjusted the underline, we can change the font family for the whole text in the :guilabel:`Paragraph` tab."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:68
msgid "This can be used with any of the :ref:`text_character_properties`, and can be used to keep consistency in a text while still being able to style each character individually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:71
msgid "Using Glyph Alternates"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:73
msgid "Some fonts have alternate :term:`glyphs` for specific characters for decorative effects. To access them, you can use the :ref:`text_property_open_type` in the text properties docker, but it is more convenient to use the :ref:`glyph_palette`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:75
msgid "To open the glyph palette, go to the Text Tool options, and press :guilabel:`Glyph Palette`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:80
msgid "If there's a text active, and the font supports glyph alternates for the given glyph, it will be show in the palette."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:82
msgid "Double |mouseleft| an alternate glyph to select it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:85
msgid "Curving And Per-Character Positioning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:87
msgid "Sometimes you want to have more control over the position of the :term:`glyphs`. You can do this with the :ref:`type_setting_mode` in the Text Tool options. First ensure that the text is preformatted by selecting :guilabel:`Preformatted` in the Text Tool options. Then, click the :guilabel:`Type Setting Mode` button to enable it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:95
msgid "The selection area on canvas will now have been replaced with a series of lines. And two dots will be at the start and end of the selection area. You can |mouseleft| + drag the dots to move the whole selection."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:100
msgid "While this is powerful, sometimes you want to have the whole text follow a path without having to adjust every character individually."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:102
msgid "To do so, first, create a path on a vector layer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:107
msgid "Then hover over the path with the :ref:`text_tool`, and press |mouseleft|."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:112
msgid "You will now be able to adjust the text postion on the path, and with the :ref:`shape_edit_tool` you can adjust the path. You will first need to go into contour mode (the top right icon) and then select and edit the path as usual."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:114
msgid "To hide the path, use the :ref:`shape_selection_tool` to select it and set the opacity to 0%."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:119
msgid "Finally, if these two functions don't do what you need them to do, there's always :guilabel:`Convert to Path` in the :ref:`shape_edit_tool` options. Using this will convert the text into a regular vector shape (if you have multiple colors in use, it will produce a group shape, so you will need to ungroup with the :ref:`shape_selection_tool` context menu)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:122
msgid "Comics"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:124
msgid "When creating a comic, you can add text at any given moment. The examples here focus on the most common moments: At the very start, when planning a comic, or at the very end, when type setting a comic."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:126
msgid "Now, when creating a comic, it is important that the text is consistent and and easy to read. To ensure that, you can use :ref:`resource_style_presets`. First, create a text. Then, with the :ref:`text_properties_docker`, set the preferred font, and the font size. Finally, create a style preset by going to the :guilabel:`Preset` tab, and there selecting :guilabel:`New Preset`. A dialog will pop up, where you can set the name and the style sample."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:131
msgid "Now, you can go into the tool options for the Text Tool, and untick :guilabel:`Current Text Properties`, then select your new preset in the dropdown. New texts will now be created with that preset, making it easy to keep everything consistent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:135
msgid "It can be tricky to determine a readable font size, as images on screen are bigger or smaller than their printed outputs depending on the screen. This is because programs like Krita display images so that at 100% a single pixel in the image is a single pixel on the screen. But it is possible to switch to physical size too. There's a button next to the zoom slider at the bottom that allows you to switch between pixel sizing and physical sizing. When switched to physical sizing, Krita will display the image zoomed to its physical size at 100%."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:137
msgid "To determine a readable font size, you then create a text with your preferred font. Then switch to physical size. If you work at twice the physical size, you will need to zoom to 50%, if not, zoom to 100%. Then, sit at an arms' length from the monitor, and adjust the font size of the text until it is pleasant to read."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:139
msgid "If you don't work for print, you can skip the physical zoom step, and instead adjust the zoom so that it is the same size on screen as the end result. Then adjust the font size as necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:142
msgid "Planning A Comic"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:144
msgid "Methods that put text onto a comic at the very start do so because the artist wants to make sure that the text has enough room, and they plan the images around the text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:146
msgid "Now, you might be working off a script or a very rough sketch. The first thing you do then is create new texts. You can do this with the :ref:`text_tool`, by |mouseleft| + dragging a large rectangle to create a :ref:`text_inline_wrapped` area. Then type your text. This inline-wrapped length is useful here because it doesn't cut off at any given point, so you can focus on typing text and adjusting it afterwards."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:148
msgid "You can use the :ref:`shape_selection_tool` to select multiple text shapes and adjust them with the :ref:`text_properties_docker`. This will only affect the :guilabel:`Paragraph` level properties."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:153
msgid "A rough layout of a comic of five panels. Panel 1: Boy sees something, and says \"Huh?\". Panel 2: A girl's back. Panel 3: Boy yells \"Hey, don't go there!\". Panel 4: Girl turns, looks confused, \"What do you mean?\". Panel 5: We see boy's face, past the girl's back of the head. \"You don't know?\", \"It's super dangerous over there!\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:153
msgid ".. image:: /images/text/working_text_planning_comics.png"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:153
msgid "With all the texts in place, this comic page is ready to be pencilled. By having the texts laid out like this, it becomes clear to see how much space there is left for the images."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:156
msgid "Type Setting A Comic"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:158
msgid "The other method of putting text on comics is at the very end, after all colors and images are finished. This is usually referred to as \"Type Setting\" a comic, as it is not just about putting the text in place, but also making it look good together with the images."
msgstr ""

