#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:186
msgid "Vertical Text"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:188
msgid "To make a vertical text, create a text with the Text Tool. Then go to the :ref:`text_properties_docker`, into the :guilabel:`Paragraph` tab. Go to :guilabel:`Add Property` at the bottom, and select :ref:`text_property_writing_mode`. There you can switch it to :guilabel:`Vertical, Right to Left` to set the whole text vertical."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:190
msgid "It can be useful to create a Style Preset for this if you use it frequently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:194
msgid "At this moment, Krita does not support mixed writing modes or text orientations."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:197
msgid "Right To Left Text"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:199
msgid "While Krita does implement a :term:`Bidirectional` algorithm, you do need to explicitly set the direction of the paragraph. For a right-to-left paragraph, create a text. Then go to the :ref:`text_properties_docker`, into the :guilabel:`Paragraph` tab. Go to :guilabel:`Add Property` at the bottom, and select :ref:`text_property_direction`. Set that to :guilabel:`Right To Left`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:201
msgid "This will initialize the Bidirectional algorithm properly. It will also make sure that :ref:`text_property_text_align` will switch the meaning of :guilabel:`Start` and :guilabel:`End`. Finally, it will show the :ref:`Unicode Bidi <text_property_direction>` property in the :guilabel:`Character` tab, which can be used to fine-tune the behaviour of the Bidirectional algorithm."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:204
msgid "Text Term Glossary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:206
msgid "There's a number of technical terms that are used throughout the manual to describe certain functionality. These technical terms are so common that it is easier to provide a glossary of their meanings than to explain them every time their come up."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:209
msgid "Characters"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:211
msgid "This refers to individual letters in a text. \"Individual\" is doing a lot of heavy lifting here, as not all languages have unique letters, but instead use clusters of letters that get represented by a single glyph. In any case, within the documentation we'll be using character to refer to the text as it is typed, and glyph to refer to the pictures that make up the text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:212
msgid "Glyphs"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:214
msgid "This is the name of the image or vector shape that represents a character or cluster of characters. The glyph selected is determined by the font, language and any OpenType features that are enabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:215
msgid "OpenType"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:217
msgid "Fonts are not just collections of glyphs for each character and cluster, but also contain a tiny program that instructs the text layout how to use the glyphs. OpenType is a standard for these programs, and Krita allows you to configure the features of the program via various OpenType feature controls."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:218
msgid "Advance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:220
msgid "This refers to how much space a glyph takes up in the line its laid out in. Sometimes this is bigger or smaller than the size of the glyph itself, and is influenced by properties like Kerning and Letter spacing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:221
msgid "Kerning"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:223
msgid "When you have a line of text, you put the glyphs next to one another. Sometimes this can lead to little gaps appearing between some glyph combinations. Fonts usually have a list of places where this happens and instruct the text layout to pull the glyphs back a little, so the gap closes. This is called Kerning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:224
msgid "Bidirectional"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user_manual/working_with_text.rst:226
msgid "Some scripts are written left-to-right, while others are written right-to-left. When a text has a mix of both, it needs to sort and adjust each segment so the words in each script stay together. For this there's the Unicode bidirectional algorithm."
msgstr ""
